<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Tournament Reports</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="07436287fe3056b696283e267ce1cd7e" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Tournament Reports</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/treports/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/heroclix/treports/treports.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/vs/treports/treports.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/lotr/treports/treports.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/treports/treports.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/treports/treports.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Black Rider Tournament - Bozeman MT 10-6<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=15156'>Mary "X-calibur" Kirby</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=15156&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> October 10, 2003</font><p align='justify'><blockquote><font class="bfont"> Black Rider Tournament, Bozeman MT  – Monday Oct 6th, 2003<br />
 <br />
Interestingly enough, this is my first tournament report on probably the last tournament I will get to attend for a long time.  I don’t remember a great deal of detail being old and senile but I will try to do my best.  And I’m really sorry that I don’t remember any of my opponent’s names except for Curtis.  <br />
<br />
Morning of Oct 6th, my daughter, Jennifer picked me up at around 11:30 am and we went into Missoula.  She had a class that lasted from 12 to 1 and then we were going to leave from the U of M to head to Bozeman.  So I had an hour or so to kill in Missoula which I spent getting gas, visiting an ATM and getting lunch.  Then I met her at the U again and we headed out on the road. Jennifer does not play (except Star Trek when she was younger but that’s another story) but she wanted to visit some friends in Belgrade which is just before Bozeman so she offered to drive.  I hate driving so was very willing to let her do so.   Fortunately for me she likes to drive so I didn’t have to.  <br />
We arrived in Bozeman around 4 pm and the tournament wasn’t until 6 so I hung out at the shop, looked through Roger’s (the shop owner) binders and then at 5 the Helena contingent arrived.  Adam and Thomas came out and we decided to play some warm up games just for fun.  I played Adam first and he was playing a HiDaN deck with a Moria archery shadow.  My fellowship which was the Roamin’ Ranger’s one took the shadow without much problem but he went first and my Issy Orc shadow could never slow his fellowship down.  HiDaN in Adam’s hands is a powerful fellowship indeed.  And I never did draw GBHB until site 7 or 8 I think (don’t remember for sure.  Just that it was too late to do me any good)  I then played with Thomas and I really don’t remember a lot about this game.  About that time the Bozeman players arrived and things got a bit hectic.  He was playing Uruk Site control for the shadow though.  I do remember that all too well.  So we had to quit at around site 6 and I believe that he was a site ahead of me but I’m not sure.  <br />
So then Jen Muncy introduced Sean Smallman (the Black Rider) and he went over the Draft rules and we divided up into 2 groups to draft.  My group included Sean, Jen and Julia but I don’t remember who else was there.  I got the Ents-discarding Hobbits with Southron draft pack.  Two cultures that I had never played with before, grrrrrreat! (more grrrrr than great).  So we started drafting and I saw in the first pack, Smeagol, PC which I snagged right away.  Then in the next pack was Ent Horde which I also snagged.  Then I saw  some misc.  Dunland minions and a couple of the Sauron wraiths.   Then I got some Gandy pumps and a couple of tree pumps.  Then luck would have it I got 2 Treebeards in a row and then an Ent Avenger.  Bound by Rage for my Dunland dudes and an Orc Insurgent.  Wish I could have drafted a few more of the Wisps.  I picked up 2 of them though.  And a Kept Safe and a few Smeagol pumps and Faramir, Sod which I thought was a good thing , ha.  <br />
Anyway I went ahead and formed my deck with 9 companions.  I also had drawn an extra merry which was really a good thing in 2 of my games.  So my starting fellowship consisted of Merry, Pip, Quickbeam and Smeagol.  Draw deck was Gandalf, TWW, Treebeardx2, Ent Horde, Ent Avenger, extra Merry and Faramir, SoD.  So you already see the problem - too many companions. So I was going to have to just discard somebody.  <br />
Shadow was a Raider/Dunland/Sauron mess with a misc Uruk thrown in.  It was all minions except 2 Bound By Rages and 1 Too Long Have These Peasants Stood.  <br />
1st game against Curtis:  He had an elf/rohan/gondor  fellowship with uruk type shadow and he went first.  I found that the trees work very well but having Faramir in the fellowship was a big mistake.  By having him in there I was forced to not play Treebeard.  And Treebeard would have been much more useful.  I didn’t do too badly but my shadow couldn’t stop him and he waltzed into site 9 without much opposition.  I did learn that my shadow wasn’t going to stop anyone and that trees are really tough so I decided in my other 2 games that I would definitely drop Faramir, the Smeagol pumps which I never used and put in all the Tree pumps I’d pulled.  <br />
FL – +1 <br />
Props:  To Curtis who played an excellent game and didn’t make stupid mistakes.<br />
Slops : To me for making stupid little mistakes and for having Faramir in the deck and for being stupid and not running like you know what.  <br />
2nd game against one of the girls (was the g/f of another player but I forget her name, sorry)  <br />
She too was playing Elfs/Rohan/Aragorn and Uruks/Issy Orcs which seemed to be a pretty popular combo.  This time I bid to go first and I ran all the way.  Surprisingly this game my shadow was stopping her.  The Easterlings got the burdens on and other ones spotted burdens to be fierce and pumped up.  And I was able to get enough burdens to play Dead people as well.  Only problem was that I made a real newbies mistake, (stupid stupid stupid) and forgot to heal my guys at site 6.  A mistake that any idiot knows not to make and I did it.  Geez!   Anyway by the time I had run to site 9 I had lost Smeagol and she dropped 9 minions on me so Frodo was overwhelmed.  <br />
FL +2<br />
<br />
Props:  To her for holding all those minions and tempting me into double moving.  She played an excellent game also.  <br />
Slops:  To me for that stupid stupid stupid newbie mistake of not healing at site 6.  Who knows what might have happened if I had done so?  <br />
<br />
Game 3:  against a nice guy whose name I don’t remember either (I am going to have to write these names down.).  Played with the fellowship of the day, Rohan/Elves/Gondor.  Shadow was again Uruks with Sauron Trolls this time.  <br />
We had a great time with this game, very relaxed because we knew by then we weren’t going to be winning anything so we could have a good time.  This game I did run again though not as fast.  He got some Uruks and the Trolls out against me but my trees did survive nicely.  Only thing I really remember about this game was that at one point he forgot to draw and started playing his fellowship guys.  He realized it as soon as he played Anborn .  I told him that he could go ahead and draw the 4 cards he would have drawn anyway.  I figured neither one of us were going to win anything anyway so why be a butthead?  Anyway I got into site 9 ahead of him with all 9 of my fellowship intact.  <br />
He was able to get 8 minions out but that wasn’t enough to take my fellowship.  So he conceded the game, picked up all the twilight and then realized that he was at the Palantir Chamber (his site).  So then he wanted to go back and redo the whole thing.  Which I said no to because not only had he picked up the twilight so we’d have to reconstruct the whole fellowship and shadow phase but he had also shuffled his discard pile and made it his draw deck.  So he had no discard pile to get minions from.  Anyway, he seemed pretty disappointed by it so I showed him that with 4 burdens he’d only pull 2 minions anyway.  And that would be 10 minions to my 9 companions but one of those companions was Ent Horde so it would automatically be def +1 since there were more minions than companions.  He pointed out that his smallest minion was an 8 which would overwhelm Frodo but I pointed out that I would just put on the One Ring which would give Frodo +2 to strength making him a 5 and not overwhelmed.  This is the one time that I’ve been really thankful I had Mr. Bubbles for the Ring.  So I won that one but it was way too close for my comfort.  <br />
FW +5<br />
<br />
Props:  To my opponent for making the game very relaxed and fun. Also to him for being able to get 2 Trolls out against me and to my fellowship for surviving that.   To ATAR which was the difference between my winning and losing.<br />
Slops:  To my shadow which again didn’t do an awful lot.  <br />
<br />
Overall winners: <br />
<br />
Adam Prody - first<br />
 Thomas Harris – second<br />
 Curtis Edwards - third. <br />
Rich ?? -  random <br />
Christina ?? -  Fierce award <br />
<br />
Jen Muncy beat the Sean Smallman, the Black Rider.<br />
<br />
Props:  To Jen Muncy for organizing a great tournament and for nagging Decipher until they sent us a Black Rider to shut us up.  To Sean Smallman who was a great sport, staying late to play everyone who wanted to play him.  To Roger for being willing to keep his shop open for us on a Monday night and being willing to put up with us too.  <br />
To my daughter, Jennifer, for being willing to drive all the way to Bozeman so I could participate in the tournament.  To Adam and Thomas, two of my favorite Helena people for the games before and also for winning the tournament – way to go guys.  To Jen Muncy who is a lot like me in that she seldom wins, for beating Sean and bringing home the booty. To everyone at the tournament for making it a wonderful last tournament to remember for me.  <br />
Slops:  Can’t think of a thing.  It was awesome!<br />
<br />
We finally left about 11:30 PM and got back into Stevensville (where I live - 25 miles south of Missoula) about 3 AM.  And I had to get up at 6 AM.  But I wouldn’t have missed it.  <br />
Anyway, until next time whenever that will be.  <br />
<br />
X-calibur<br />
<br />
